  "texts": [
    "Following the theoretical framework of dialogue games, we can characterize systems by their ability along the following three dimensions: (i) supported dialogue types, (ii) ability to adapt to the user, and (iii) explicitness of goal.",
    "We discuss the systems along these lines in more detail below.",
    "Supported dialogue types Some systems, such as those proposed by Hernandez-Bocanegra and Ziegler (2023) and Malandri et al. (2023), incorporate mechanisms to clarify ambiguous user requests.",
    "However, while Madumal et al. (2019) advocate for systems that can detect false premises in questions, we found no system with this feature.",
    "Allowing users to challenge or inquire further about provided explanations makes the dialogues more human-like."
  ],
